        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-08-02 12:15:40.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1\n\nPer Sonar:\nThe constant interface pattern is a poor use of interfaces.\n\nThat a class uses some constants internally is an implementation detail.\n\nImplementing a constant interface causes this implementation detail to leak into the class's exported API. It is of no consequence to the users of a class that the class implements a constant interface. In fact, it may even confuse them. Worse, it represents a commitment: if in a future release the class is modified so that it no longer needs to use the constants, it still must implement the interface to ensure binary compatibility. If a nonfinal class implements a constant interface,\n\nall of its subclasses will have their namespaces polluted by the constants in the interface.\n\nThe recommendation is to use a class or enum.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "1f508bd9970ec49c9d45dd31e37c1b671d3488a8",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-08-02 12:29:14.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> Jim, have to get familiar with @Property annotation to do the work,\n > but can it do, \"flattened\" hierarchical property naming handling?  \n > Thing here, property name is not fixed .. ie. http.server.services.X.https\n > and http.server.services.Z.https ..\n > \n > Point being the property names are unbound and not known a priori. \n > So, question is if @Property supports such functionality?\n\nIf I understand the question, there's a helper class, SpecProperties that helps with that.  In the above example, you'd create: sp = SpecProperties(\"http.server.services.\"+serviceName, props).  Then you can do sp.getProperty(\"https.xxx\"), etc.  (Or include the \".https\" in the constructor, if that's preferred.)  You'd pass \"sp\" instead of \"props\" to the PropertyConfiguration subclass.  The same kind of thing is done in the pooling example, where the property names have the controller name in the prefix",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "92767d69a39fe5b865ec34b1ecb7c3c2f0ef8380",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2787,
          "name": "Liam Fallon",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "liam.fallon@est.tech",
          "username": "liamfallon"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-08-02 13:15:49.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nIt would be a big job to change but the reason we used the approach in common-parameters for configuration was to get around the limitations with Java properties that they are flat, untyped, and not validated.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "7ea5cdf87881e672ab4f802ea31ad286f4f4bfa9",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-08-02 15:52:01.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1\n\nMaybe we should just go with this as it is, and I can retrofit the properties after it's merged.  I still prefer the constants to be moved out of the interfaces, particularly since this is new code, but I'm not dead set on that either.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
